WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.080
Thank you, everyone, for your time today.

00:00:08.080 --> 00:00:09.480
Just a quick recap of our agenda.

00:00:09.480 --> 00:00:14.480
We're going to be starting talking about some of the challenges that data science teams

00:00:14.480 --> 00:00:20.920
face and how RStudio products can help tackle those challenges, and how those challenges

00:00:20.920 --> 00:00:25.719
then help drive people to consider moving to the cloud.

00:00:25.719 --> 00:00:29.959
And so then we'll talk about some of the different cloud options that are out there, hosted services,

00:00:30.920 --> 00:00:37.240
working with a VPC provider such as Azure or AWS, cloud marketplace offerings, and doing

00:00:37.240 --> 00:00:39.759
data science in your data lake.

00:00:39.759 --> 00:00:44.799
And then I'll hand off to Kevin to do a deep dive on some of the factors that you should

00:00:44.799 --> 00:00:50.480
consider when you are considering deploying your software to a VPC.

00:00:50.480 --> 00:00:54.279
Then we'll wrap up and have time for as many questions as we can.

00:00:54.279 --> 00:00:58.200
And as Sam said, any questions we don't get to today, we'll have a follow-up thread on

00:00:58.200 --> 00:01:03.720
our community site to continue the discussion there.

00:01:03.720 --> 00:01:09.360
So we've talked to many data science teams in a large variety of organizations over the

00:01:09.360 --> 00:01:10.360
years.

00:01:10.360 --> 00:01:14.839
And what we've heard from many of them is that a lot of data science teams fail to live

00:01:14.839 --> 00:01:20.800
up to their full promise of what they're trying to achieve, what the organization is hoping,

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:24.480
the value that the organization is hoping to get from this team.

00:01:24.480 --> 00:01:27.120
And there's lots of reasons for that.

00:01:27.120 --> 00:01:32.279
And these reasons tend to group, based on our conversations with, again, many data science

00:01:32.279 --> 00:01:35.360
teams, tend to group into a few different areas.

00:01:35.360 --> 00:01:38.919
Perhaps teams have trouble creating insights.

00:01:38.919 --> 00:01:43.040
Perhaps they have trouble, once they have actually created those insights, to actually

00:01:43.040 --> 00:01:48.160
use those insights to impact decision-making in the organization, because ultimately, if

00:01:48.160 --> 00:01:52.080
you've got a better way to do things or a better way to make a decision, it only actually

00:01:52.080 --> 00:01:57.720
matters if that gets implemented and that actually impacts your organization.

00:01:57.720 --> 00:02:02.519
Or sometimes teams have the greatest challenges around actually maintaining and improving

00:02:02.519 --> 00:02:07.839
this value over time, that they get some insights, they create decision-making, but then it fades.

00:02:07.839 --> 00:02:10.520
Maybe they find it difficult to maintain.

00:02:10.520 --> 00:02:15.839
So there are many different reasons, many different challenges that go into these different

00:02:15.839 --> 00:02:19.240
areas and things that teams need to overcome.

00:02:19.240 --> 00:02:24.639
Today we're going to be focusing on this third column, that siloed teams lead to often

00:02:24.639 --> 00:02:28.000
redundant work, make collaboration difficult.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:32.800
They may spend too much time maintaining tools or too much time re-running analyses because

00:02:32.800 --> 00:02:36.679
teams can't easily deploy self-service applications.

00:02:36.679 --> 00:02:41.479
Or perhaps it takes too much manual effort to deploy and maintain these systems.

00:02:41.479 --> 00:02:46.759
And I'm focusing on these because these are the items that are often addressed by centralizing

00:02:46.759 --> 00:02:52.080
your data science and or moving it to the cloud.

00:02:52.080 --> 00:02:57.199
So what we found is that customers who have successfully scaled their data science team

00:02:57.199 --> 00:03:02.279
and the work that they do and impacted their organization tend to focus on three key attributes

00:03:02.279 --> 00:03:07.399
of their data science environment, open source, code-oriented, and centralized.

00:03:07.399 --> 00:03:11.279
And again, in this session, we'll focus on the centralized and cloud aspect.

00:03:11.279 --> 00:03:15.440
Open source, of course, is a key part of our studio's mission, and we find it critical

00:03:15.440 --> 00:03:19.479
because it eases recruiting and retention and training for new people and it's comprehensive

00:03:19.479 --> 00:03:22.240
and interoperable.

00:03:22.240 --> 00:03:26.279
Code-oriented is a key part of our studio's philosophy of data science because code is

00:03:26.279 --> 00:03:28.199
flexible.

00:03:28.199 --> 00:03:33.220
It doesn't have black box constraints and code by its nature is easy to iterate and

00:03:33.220 --> 00:03:36.360
reuse and extend and inspect.

00:03:36.360 --> 00:03:41.160
But again, in this session, we'll focus on the centralized and cloud aspects because

00:03:41.160 --> 00:03:46.479
centralizing your data science helps reduce unnecessary work for the data science team,

00:03:46.479 --> 00:03:52.800
makes it easier to collaborate across that team, providing a common way of deploying

00:03:52.800 --> 00:03:57.479
self-service applications to your stakeholders, helps inform them, helps drive decision making

00:03:57.479 --> 00:04:00.080
and impact that in the organization.

00:04:00.080 --> 00:04:04.240
And of course, if you're working with open source tools like R and Python, finding some

00:04:04.240 --> 00:04:08.679
consistent way to manage all the data science packages and manage the versions of that is

00:04:08.679 --> 00:04:09.740
critical.

00:04:09.740 --> 00:04:13.539
And often that's easiest if you centralize that so that it's common across both your

00:04:13.539 --> 00:04:19.179
development and deployment environments.

00:04:19.179 --> 00:04:25.579
Now these three key aspects, open source, code-oriented, and centralized, are key aspects

00:04:25.579 --> 00:04:28.179
of what we call serious data science.

00:04:28.179 --> 00:04:32.420
And we call this serious data science because this approach typically enables a data scientist

00:04:32.420 --> 00:04:39.059
to tackle the complex, difficult, and at least initially often ill-defined problems that

00:04:39.059 --> 00:04:44.380
can really provide value and novel insights in an organization.

00:04:44.380 --> 00:04:50.459
Now the two leading languages in open source data science are, of course, R and Python.

00:04:50.459 --> 00:04:55.380
But on their own, R and Python certainly provide the open source and code-oriented aspects,

00:04:55.380 --> 00:05:00.100
but they don't out of the box on their own make it easy to centralize your data science

00:05:00.100 --> 00:05:02.040
or deploy it to the cloud.

00:05:02.040 --> 00:05:06.140
And that's where RStudio's commercial products come in.

00:05:06.140 --> 00:05:10.140
Our products support the development and deployment of data science with both R and

00:05:10.140 --> 00:05:11.660
Python.

00:05:11.660 --> 00:05:15.980
And we have a modular platform called RStudio Team that helps you centralize your data science

00:05:15.980 --> 00:05:21.500
in an enterprise-friendly way, providing security and scalability, et cetera.

00:05:21.500 --> 00:05:24.859
And so let's just talk about that briefly.

00:05:24.859 --> 00:05:28.220
Now what does a data science team actually need to do?

00:05:28.220 --> 00:05:32.059
Well there's two things that they typically need to do in part of their work.

00:05:32.059 --> 00:05:36.579
They need to create insights, and then they need to find a way of sharing those insights

00:05:36.579 --> 00:05:40.459
to impact decision-making in the organization.

00:05:40.459 --> 00:05:45.500
And so typically when they create insights, they're using some sort of data science workbench,

00:05:45.500 --> 00:05:50.940
some way where they can use their IDE of choice, whether it's Jupyter Notebooks or the RStudio

00:05:50.940 --> 00:05:58.739
IDE or VS Code, all in a single location, use those different development environments

00:05:58.820 --> 00:06:02.619
to create various data products using R and Python.

00:06:02.619 --> 00:06:06.220
These typically are tailored applications or reports or APIs.

00:06:06.220 --> 00:06:10.700
We call these tailored because they're not off the shelf, they're not black box, but

00:06:10.700 --> 00:06:15.619
they're focused on the problem at hand, focused on providing the exact information that a

00:06:15.619 --> 00:06:19.220
decision-maker needs in their day-to-day work.

00:06:19.220 --> 00:06:22.500
And that's one of the big advantages, of course, of a code-oriented approach.

00:06:22.500 --> 00:06:24.660
You don't have any arbitrary limitations.

00:06:24.660 --> 00:06:27.700
You can focus on what your stakeholders need.

00:06:27.700 --> 00:06:32.700
And of course, once they create these interactive applications or reports or APIs, they need

00:06:32.700 --> 00:06:36.059
a way of publishing them, a way of sharing them.

00:06:36.059 --> 00:06:39.859
And so typically they can publish these to a deployment portal, and once this is available

00:06:39.859 --> 00:06:47.019
in a deployment portal, the data science team can now share these insights to impact decision-making.

00:06:47.019 --> 00:06:52.579
And this typically takes the form of an interactive web application, say a Shiny application that

00:06:52.579 --> 00:06:57.420
can be shared with a decision-maker, or an automated email report that can be sent to

00:06:57.420 --> 00:07:02.019
the decision-maker with the analysis right within it, so they have that data within their

00:07:02.019 --> 00:07:04.140
inbox.

00:07:04.140 --> 00:07:11.579
Or perhaps they create APIs that can be integrated into other systems for automated decision-making.

00:07:11.579 --> 00:07:15.459
And it's critical for both these areas, for both the development side and the deployment

00:07:15.459 --> 00:07:20.420
side, that you have a way of managing your open source packages, because this eases maintenance

00:07:20.420 --> 00:07:24.059
and reproducibility.

00:07:24.059 --> 00:07:26.100
And this, of course, is where our products come in.

00:07:26.100 --> 00:07:31.619
RStudio Server Pro provides that centralized data science workbench with a variety of different

00:07:31.619 --> 00:07:33.179
development environments.

00:07:33.179 --> 00:07:38.820
RStudio Connect provides that deployment portal where you can share your applications and

00:07:38.820 --> 00:07:42.380
APIs with your decision-makers and other systems.

00:07:42.380 --> 00:07:48.459
And these may take the form of Shiny, RMarkdown, Plumber APIs, also a number of different Python

00:07:48.859 --> 00:07:54.260
frameworks that we support, things like Streamlet and Bokeh.

00:07:54.260 --> 00:07:57.700
And it's critical for both of these that you have a way of managing packages, and that's

00:07:57.700 --> 00:08:00.059
where RStudio Package Manager comes in.

00:08:00.059 --> 00:08:04.459
And it's these three products, RStudio Server Pro, Connect, and Package Manager, that make

00:08:04.459 --> 00:08:09.700
up our RStudio team bundle.

00:08:09.700 --> 00:08:14.899
And of course, it's critical that this all integrates with standard systems in your organization.

00:08:15.059 --> 00:08:19.660
Kevin will be talking a lot more about a few of these, especially Kubernetes moving forward.

00:08:19.660 --> 00:08:26.260
But the critical idea here is there's a lot of benefits to centralizing your data science.

00:08:26.260 --> 00:08:32.059
And many, many of our customers do exactly this on-prem.

00:08:32.059 --> 00:08:37.580
And so the question is, what then drives people to want to go to the cloud?

00:08:37.580 --> 00:08:40.659
There's several different reasons.

00:08:40.659 --> 00:08:48.099
One key reason is simply simplifying and reducing the startup cost for a new data science team,

00:08:48.099 --> 00:08:53.340
that when an organization is spinning up a new team, cloud is often a way to really get

00:08:53.340 --> 00:08:58.340
that team, get the resources that team needs going quickly.

00:08:58.340 --> 00:09:02.460
Perhaps they want to make collaboration or instruction, say workshops or classes, between

00:09:02.460 --> 00:09:04.539
organizations or groups easier.

00:09:04.539 --> 00:09:07.700
Cloud's a great way of doing that.

00:09:07.739 --> 00:09:11.580
Perhaps they want to mitigate the high cost of maintaining their own computing infrastructure.

00:09:11.580 --> 00:09:17.219
This was one of the primary drivers originally for organizations to move to the cloud.

00:09:17.219 --> 00:09:21.619
It is still a major factor.

00:09:21.619 --> 00:09:24.619
Closely aligned to that is scaling to meet variable demand.

00:09:24.619 --> 00:09:29.700
That if the demand for your computations, for your data science computations is highly

00:09:29.700 --> 00:09:35.299
variable, you don't want to keep a bunch of expensive computing infrastructure sitting

00:09:35.299 --> 00:09:36.299
around idle.

00:09:36.299 --> 00:09:39.940
Instead, you want to push that responsibility out to the cloud provider to maintain that

00:09:39.940 --> 00:09:41.820
for you.

00:09:41.820 --> 00:09:47.700
And finally, if your data is already in the cloud, then you want to reduce time and costs

00:09:47.700 --> 00:09:49.859
in moving the data to your analysis.

00:09:49.859 --> 00:09:54.099
And rather than pulling it down locally to do data science, it's often much more efficient

00:09:54.099 --> 00:09:58.820
and much less expensive to do that data science up on the cloud directly right in your data

00:09:58.820 --> 00:10:01.340
lake.

00:10:01.340 --> 00:10:03.380
So let's talk about a few of these different options.

00:10:03.460 --> 00:10:12.260
Again, one of the most common options is doing a hosted service where a vendor provides software

00:10:12.260 --> 00:10:13.260
as a service.

00:10:13.260 --> 00:10:16.619
We talked about a couple of things our studio does there.

00:10:16.619 --> 00:10:20.979
The other very common way of doing this is deploying to a virtual private cloud provider

00:10:20.979 --> 00:10:23.299
such as Azure or AWS.

00:10:23.299 --> 00:10:26.859
And I'll be touching on that lightly here, but Kevin will be covering that in a lot more

00:10:26.859 --> 00:10:29.820
detail in the next section.

00:10:29.820 --> 00:10:32.260
Third and closely aligned is cloud marketplace offerings.

00:10:32.260 --> 00:10:35.859
Again, that's very similar in some ways to deploying to a VPC.

00:10:35.859 --> 00:10:39.099
You're running on the cloud provider's hardware.

00:10:39.099 --> 00:10:44.900
But here, typically it's easier to start up and it's done on an hourly basis.

00:10:44.900 --> 00:10:51.539
And finally, data science in a data lake such as Qball or Databricks.

00:10:51.539 --> 00:10:54.580
So hosted software as service offerings.

00:10:54.580 --> 00:10:58.380
Some of the things that really make these offerings great are they're easy to quickly

00:10:58.380 --> 00:11:01.380
start up and they streamline collaboration.

00:11:01.500 --> 00:11:05.700
So if the members of your team can simply go in, put a credit card in and sign up for

00:11:05.700 --> 00:11:13.219
a few dollars a month to access some capabilities, that's an easy way to scale up very quickly.

00:11:13.219 --> 00:11:19.340
Now sometimes software as service may have limited functionality compared to on-prem.

00:11:19.340 --> 00:11:24.340
So you might not have the full option that you would have if you were to install locally.

00:11:24.340 --> 00:11:28.659
And sometimes again, depending on the service, integration with your data internal systems

00:11:28.659 --> 00:11:32.739
could be more challenging or perhaps not even possible.

00:11:32.739 --> 00:11:36.580
So a couple of offerings that RStudio has in this arena.

00:11:36.580 --> 00:11:42.659
We have RStudio Cloud, which is a hosted version of the RStudio Server Pro with the RStudio

00:11:42.659 --> 00:11:43.659
IDE.

00:11:43.659 --> 00:11:48.460
It makes it easy for anybody to do or share or teach or learn data science using just

00:11:48.460 --> 00:11:50.400
your web browser.

00:11:50.400 --> 00:11:56.780
So the initial focus right now for RStudio Cloud is primarily as a platform for instructor-led

00:11:56.780 --> 00:11:57.780
education.

00:11:58.659 --> 00:12:02.859
So if you were doing a workshop in your commercial organization or if you were teaching a class

00:12:02.859 --> 00:12:07.619
on data science or statistics at the university level, RStudio Cloud is a great solution for

00:12:07.619 --> 00:12:08.619
that.

00:12:08.619 --> 00:12:11.820
And we have many organizations using it for that already.

00:12:11.820 --> 00:12:18.539
Another great focus for RStudio Cloud right now is enabling academic research by sharing

00:12:18.539 --> 00:12:19.539
among different groups.

00:12:19.539 --> 00:12:22.619
It's a handy way of doing that.

00:12:22.619 --> 00:12:27.380
And there's a lot more that we'll be rolling out in RStudio Cloud over the next several

00:12:27.380 --> 00:12:28.380
months.

00:12:28.380 --> 00:12:33.539
So some of the great benefits of RStudio Cloud, again, nothing to install locally.

00:12:33.539 --> 00:12:35.219
All you need is a browser.

00:12:35.219 --> 00:12:39.460
You can share projects that you create there with your team or a class or workshop.

00:12:39.460 --> 00:12:44.059
And again, nothing to configure, no hardware installation or anything like that, just a

00:12:44.059 --> 00:12:46.859
month-to-month purchase.

00:12:46.859 --> 00:12:54.700
And there's various plans available for RStudio Cloud, including free to get started.

00:12:54.940 --> 00:12:57.859
ShinyApps.io is another hosted service RStudio provides.

00:12:57.859 --> 00:13:05.419
This is a way of securely and scalably sharing your Shiny applications on a hosted service.

00:13:05.419 --> 00:13:09.140
And so if you have a Shiny application that you want to share with the world or with a

00:13:09.140 --> 00:13:13.539
much smaller group, you can do that quickly on ShinyApps.io.

00:13:13.539 --> 00:13:18.059
Again, various plans available there, including free to get started.

00:13:18.059 --> 00:13:23.059
You can visit ShinyApps.io to learn more.

00:13:23.059 --> 00:13:30.260
The second major area of cloud, second major way of going to the cloud is deploying to

00:13:30.260 --> 00:13:37.059
a virtual private cloud provider like AWS or Azure or Google Cloud Platform.

00:13:37.059 --> 00:13:41.979
Now some of the advantages of this is that you can pay as you go for the compute resources

00:13:41.979 --> 00:13:42.979
specifically.

00:13:42.979 --> 00:13:47.500
Typically, if you're deploying to a VPC, you've purchased the license from the vendor already,

00:13:47.500 --> 00:13:51.820
though not necessarily, depends on the offering.

00:13:51.820 --> 00:13:55.059
Another great advantage here, you get the full functionality of the on-premise software

00:13:55.059 --> 00:13:59.739
because typically it is the on-premise software or a close variant of that that's available

00:13:59.739 --> 00:14:02.299
on the VPC.

00:14:02.299 --> 00:14:09.979
So for example, right now, RStudio Cloud doesn't yet have the ability to provide Jupyter Notebooks

00:14:09.979 --> 00:14:10.979
in that environment.

00:14:10.979 --> 00:14:13.500
That's one of the things we're working on for the future.

00:14:13.500 --> 00:14:19.020
But right now, if you were to deploy RStudio Server Pro to a VPC, you'd have the full functionality

00:14:19.020 --> 00:14:24.700
of being able to utilize Jupyter Notebooks and JupyterLab through the same capabilities

00:14:24.700 --> 00:14:26.979
that you'd use the RStudio IDE.

00:14:26.979 --> 00:14:32.900
VPCs also give you access to specialized hardware like GPUs.

00:14:32.900 --> 00:14:35.380
Now on the con side, it can be difficult to maintain.

00:14:35.380 --> 00:14:38.340
There's typically more administration overhead.

00:14:38.340 --> 00:14:42.619
There's a complexity of things like Kubernetes that you might need to consider.

00:14:42.619 --> 00:14:47.780
And Kevin is going to be discussing all this in a lot more detail in the next section.

00:14:47.780 --> 00:14:54.219
The other challenge around VPCs is that the cost can be high and variable, that you need

00:14:54.219 --> 00:14:58.340
to really manage the compute cost closely to make sure the software is only available

00:14:58.340 --> 00:14:59.340
when it's needed.

00:14:59.340 --> 00:15:05.500
Otherwise, it can keep running in the background and rack up your compute charges.

00:15:05.500 --> 00:15:12.739
Third, and again, closely related, is cloud marketplace offerings.

00:15:12.739 --> 00:15:19.979
Instead of installing on your own on a VPC, you go to the AWS or Azure or GCP cloud marketplaces

00:15:19.979 --> 00:15:22.460
to spin up software from a vendor.

00:15:22.460 --> 00:15:29.140
RStudio has offerings on all those marketplaces.

00:15:29.140 --> 00:15:33.219
It's very handy in a lot of ways because it's easy to get started quickly, makes it great

00:15:33.219 --> 00:15:34.619
for proof of concepts.

00:15:34.619 --> 00:15:40.820
You're paying as you go typically for both compute and software licenses on an hourly

00:15:40.820 --> 00:15:41.820
basis.

00:15:41.900 --> 00:15:47.260
It's very inexpensive to get started, and again, access to the specialized hardware.

00:15:47.260 --> 00:15:52.219
But like deploying to a VPC, you need to make sure you carefully manage the software to

00:15:52.219 --> 00:15:54.940
make sure it's only running when you need it.

00:15:54.940 --> 00:16:00.059
Otherwise, you could run into excessive hourly charges, which means often, not always, but

00:16:00.059 --> 00:16:04.020
often this is best for short-term projects, especially if you're collaborating between

00:16:04.020 --> 00:16:10.460
organizations because that's a great way to provide access outside your organization.

00:16:10.460 --> 00:16:12.979
And then finally, data science in your data lake.

00:16:12.979 --> 00:16:17.780
Great example of a data lake is someone like Qball, a partner for RStudio.

00:16:17.780 --> 00:16:24.780
Qball provides a data lake with RStudio Server Pro capabilities built into it.

00:16:24.780 --> 00:16:29.900
And some of the advantages here is you can minimize the overhead by running your computations

00:16:29.900 --> 00:16:37.219
close to the data, avoiding the cost of moving the data from one cloud to another or down

00:16:37.219 --> 00:16:38.219
locally.

00:16:38.979 --> 00:16:44.859
It also makes it easy to incorporate data science directly into your data pipeline.

00:16:44.859 --> 00:16:49.700
Now on the con side, running your data science in your data lake can add some technical complexity,

00:16:49.700 --> 00:16:52.419
can make it a little bit more difficult to do what you want to do, or at least a little

00:16:52.419 --> 00:16:53.419
bit more complicated.

00:16:53.419 --> 00:16:58.500
And again, you might run into some functionality limitations here that could be challenging,

00:16:58.500 --> 00:17:03.380
depending on what the data lake provider and the data science provider have done and how

00:17:03.380 --> 00:17:06.060
they're working together technically.

00:17:06.900 --> 00:17:14.380
So to sum up this section, ultimately it really depends on what your primary goal is.

00:17:14.380 --> 00:17:19.660
And based on your primary goal, you can, different ways of going to the cloud.

00:17:19.660 --> 00:17:24.500
Your primary goal is to really minimize cost and maintenance and startup time, then using

00:17:24.500 --> 00:17:29.900
a hosted service is often a great way to start there, especially if you have a small team

00:17:29.900 --> 00:17:34.500
or really just an individual data scientist.

00:17:34.500 --> 00:17:39.060
If you want the full flexibility of an on-prem solution, all the bells and whistles, all

00:17:39.060 --> 00:17:43.619
the capabilities, but without maintaining your own hardware, but still having the flexibility

00:17:43.619 --> 00:17:50.459
to scale, then deploying to a VPC provider is often the best way to go.

00:17:50.459 --> 00:17:53.719
Kevin will be talking more about that next.

00:17:53.719 --> 00:17:57.660
If you're doing something that's much more short term, perhaps just a proof of concept,

00:17:57.660 --> 00:18:03.380
you don't want to commit to a long time period, offerings on a cloud marketplace by the hour

00:18:03.380 --> 00:18:05.699
are often a great way to do that.

00:18:05.699 --> 00:18:09.219
And again, if your biggest concern is your data is already in the cloud and you want

00:18:09.219 --> 00:18:14.459
to minimize the overhead of moving that data someplace else to analyze it, then often data

00:18:14.459 --> 00:18:20.579
science in your data lake is going to be the best approach.

00:18:20.579 --> 00:18:28.380
So with that, I'll hand you off to Kevin.

00:18:28.380 --> 00:18:32.060
Thank you, Lou, for that really good introduction.

00:18:32.060 --> 00:18:34.459
Really appreciate that presentation.

00:18:34.459 --> 00:18:39.300
So I want to talk about more along the lines of.

00:18:39.300 --> 00:18:44.060
Why why you might want to move to cloud and what are some of the key considerations that

00:18:44.060 --> 00:18:46.699
people have when they move to cloud?

00:18:46.699 --> 00:18:53.339
So this is a big decision for a lot of organizations to either switch from their on-premise history

00:18:53.339 --> 00:19:00.900
or or maybe just expanding their their cloud footprint for the data science teams.

00:19:00.900 --> 00:19:09.540
So next slide.

00:19:09.540 --> 00:19:15.619
So typically when we meet with clients and we're discussing cloud infrastructure for

00:19:15.619 --> 00:19:19.780
various different data science applications and primarily a lot of time we're speaking

00:19:19.780 --> 00:19:26.260
about our studio team installations and configurations, we're considering a lot of different things

00:19:26.260 --> 00:19:30.939
and the key kind of facts that come up, the key recurring themes that we see coming up

00:19:30.939 --> 00:19:34.020
are, you know, first of all, assessing the needs of the team.

00:19:34.020 --> 00:19:35.300
You know, how big is their team?

00:19:35.300 --> 00:19:40.180
How much power do they need and do they really need the cloud that they need to utilize the

00:19:40.180 --> 00:19:42.739
cloud's immense scale?

00:19:42.739 --> 00:19:46.380
And do they see a lot of potential future growth or unforeseen growth in the future?

00:19:46.380 --> 00:19:50.859
So do they need to be able to scale their their resources over time in an unpredictable

00:19:50.859 --> 00:19:51.859
manner?

00:19:51.859 --> 00:19:54.819
And this is where cloud is really powerful.

00:19:54.819 --> 00:20:01.140
It's quite easy or relatively easy to configure your environments to scale over time.

00:20:01.140 --> 00:20:05.900
If you understand where your team is going and what your needs are going to be.

00:20:05.900 --> 00:20:08.619
Another key thing is, you know, how am I going to control the cost?

00:20:08.619 --> 00:20:12.459
So with infinite scale comes infinitely scaling bills.

00:20:12.459 --> 00:20:16.459
So this is a big concern, as as Lou alluded to.

00:20:16.459 --> 00:20:22.300
It's a pay as you go model, but unfortunately, that means if you use lots and lots of resources,

00:20:22.300 --> 00:20:23.939
you're going to get charged from lots of resources.

00:20:24.060 --> 00:20:27.500
So controlling costs is a very key consideration.

00:20:27.500 --> 00:20:31.660
It's much more straightforward to control those costs when you when you are the ones

00:20:31.660 --> 00:20:35.260
maintaining the physical infrastructure, because you've got a very defined view of what it

00:20:35.260 --> 00:20:36.260
can be.

00:20:36.260 --> 00:20:42.180
But when you're dealing with virtually unlimited resources, your bills can get out of hand

00:20:42.180 --> 00:20:43.180
quite quickly.

00:20:43.180 --> 00:20:45.619
So there's different ways that you can mitigate against that.

00:20:45.619 --> 00:20:50.699
And we'll talk a little bit more about that.

00:20:50.699 --> 00:20:55.619
Another key consideration, we work with a lot of clients in more regulated industries,

00:20:55.619 --> 00:21:00.420
whether they're working in industries with proprietary information or maybe they're working

00:21:00.420 --> 00:21:05.339
in industries where they handle a lot of very sensitive data around customers.

00:21:05.339 --> 00:21:10.939
So PII that, you know, is maybe needs to be treated with a high degree of sensitivity.

00:21:10.939 --> 00:21:16.739
And this is a this is a consideration, a key consideration that maybe slows up the adoption

00:21:16.739 --> 00:21:18.540
of cloud over time.

00:21:18.540 --> 00:21:24.939
So typically, these industries are are lagging behind the more versatile or the more the

00:21:24.939 --> 00:21:28.739
more the tech industries that are maybe able to move a little quicker and these don't have

00:21:28.739 --> 00:21:32.619
these regulations that they need to consider.

00:21:32.619 --> 00:21:35.699
And so they often ask, you know, can I how can I secure my cloud?

00:21:35.699 --> 00:21:40.140
And the answer really is as secure as you want to make it.

00:21:40.140 --> 00:21:45.500
And we can dive a little bit more deep into that in a few minutes.

00:21:45.500 --> 00:21:48.900
Another key consideration is, of course, you're handing over the keys of your infrastructure

00:21:48.900 --> 00:21:50.380
to a cloud provider.

00:21:50.380 --> 00:21:55.819
And, you know, if you go back as far as the early noughties and the tech boom and there

00:21:55.819 --> 00:22:01.099
was plenty of websites that were being hosted by young entrepreneurs in in their in their

00:22:01.099 --> 00:22:05.339
home offices or their bedrooms, computers that put on their desks and they were hosting

00:22:05.339 --> 00:22:06.339
websites that way.

00:22:06.339 --> 00:22:12.099
But with the immense scale of these these cloud infrastructure companies, they're much

00:22:12.099 --> 00:22:14.020
more sophisticated organizations.

00:22:14.020 --> 00:22:18.579
And while you're handing over the keys to them and they're managing the physical security

00:22:18.579 --> 00:22:23.540
of your infrastructure, they're able to benefit from that massive scale to really secure their

00:22:23.540 --> 00:22:26.579
infrastructure in a way that is quite difficult to do.

00:22:26.579 --> 00:22:29.979
And we can talk a bit more about that.

00:22:29.979 --> 00:22:35.380
And then the last one, and this kind of ties back to our first point with regards to scale

00:22:35.380 --> 00:22:39.380
and that is, how do I adapt to change and how easy is it to do that?

00:22:39.380 --> 00:22:44.500
You know, if if I architect a solution and I build this and all of a sudden I see a huge

00:22:44.500 --> 00:22:51.380
uptick in usage and how can I make sure that we can scale our environment for our teams

00:22:51.380 --> 00:22:55.420
in an efficient manner so that we don't see any downtime or we don't have very lengthy

00:22:55.420 --> 00:22:59.300
delays between making more resources available?

00:22:59.300 --> 00:23:03.579
And again, this is somewhere where cloud can really excel if you if you know what you're

00:23:03.579 --> 00:23:05.699
doing.

00:23:05.699 --> 00:23:06.699
So yeah, thank you.

00:23:06.699 --> 00:23:12.500
You can go to the next slide, Lou.

00:23:12.500 --> 00:23:19.260
So when we initially engage with our clients, one of the first things we like to talk to

00:23:19.260 --> 00:23:25.979
them about is we carry out a series of interviews with their key users and the business users

00:23:25.979 --> 00:23:29.699
to try and get a better understanding across all the different products that they're trying

00:23:29.699 --> 00:23:31.520
to embed in their team.

00:23:31.520 --> 00:23:37.199
So as Lou mentioned, RStudio Pro for the data scientists, the people who are doing the development

00:23:37.199 --> 00:23:43.119
work, RStudio Connect, you know, the platform for sharing that information with the users

00:23:43.119 --> 00:23:50.839
and Pac-Man for sharing the sorry for controlling the managing the I.T. kind of security and

00:23:50.839 --> 00:23:55.599
package management.

00:23:55.599 --> 00:24:04.560
So I put together this small matrix just to kind of give some of those considerations

00:24:04.560 --> 00:24:06.160
that we'd like to take into account.

00:24:06.160 --> 00:24:10.280
So we're looking to understand, you know, let's say if we take, for example, RStudio

00:24:10.280 --> 00:24:12.800
Pro, how big is their team?

00:24:12.800 --> 00:24:13.800
How many?

00:24:13.800 --> 00:24:14.800
What's the makeup of the team?

00:24:14.800 --> 00:24:15.800
The context of the team?

00:24:15.800 --> 00:24:18.959
Is there a lot of data scientists, people running a lot of simulations?

00:24:18.959 --> 00:24:20.959
How variable are the workloads?

00:24:20.959 --> 00:24:22.439
What's the kind of size of data they're dealing with?

00:24:22.439 --> 00:24:26.359
Are they dealing with very small data in the order of megabytes or they're really a

00:24:26.359 --> 00:24:30.640
big data shop who are dealing with petabytes or terabytes of data?

00:24:30.640 --> 00:24:33.359
And also the size of the team definitely matters, right?

00:24:33.359 --> 00:24:37.920
If you've got a very small team, if you've got a team of five people, you know, you could

00:24:37.920 --> 00:24:42.119
probably handle your workloads and a much more simple architecture.

00:24:42.119 --> 00:24:45.959
But as you scale up your team or your scale up the size of your data, you might want to

00:24:45.959 --> 00:24:47.520
consider more complex approaches.

00:24:47.520 --> 00:24:53.880
And that's where Lou was alluding to earlier with the clusters approach with Kubernetes.

00:24:53.880 --> 00:24:55.880
And so I've kind of broken it up here.

00:24:55.880 --> 00:24:58.880
And you can think about and this is definitely a rule of thumb.

00:24:58.880 --> 00:25:01.640
And, you know, your mileage may vary, as they say.

00:25:01.640 --> 00:25:06.020
And this all comes out of a result of a series of interviews with your team and understanding

00:25:06.020 --> 00:25:07.800
your needs.

00:25:07.800 --> 00:25:11.359
But smaller teams, more simple teams would benefit from a simpler approach.

00:25:11.359 --> 00:25:12.839
And those are the ones in the yellow zone.

00:25:12.839 --> 00:25:18.119
So if you're dealing with relatively small teams with relatively small amounts of data,

00:25:18.119 --> 00:25:21.160
you could probably get away with a more basic or simple approach.

00:25:21.160 --> 00:25:25.280
Again, taking into consideration how variant is the workloads in those teams, you know,

00:25:25.280 --> 00:25:29.959
are you seeing a large differentiation and make an architecture that works for those

00:25:29.959 --> 00:25:30.959
as well?

00:25:30.959 --> 00:25:34.560
And the same with the red zone, you know, if you're dealing with very large sets of

00:25:34.560 --> 00:25:40.400
data or very large teams, you're definitely going to want to consider a more complex approach

00:25:40.959 --> 00:25:44.680
because it's just harder to predict what your team is going to be able to do.

00:25:44.680 --> 00:25:48.560
So you're maybe going to want to work with a more scalable solution, something that can

00:25:48.560 --> 00:25:51.800
flex with the needs of your team over time.

00:25:51.800 --> 00:25:54.800
And if you're sitting in that orange area again, you're going to have to think a little

00:25:54.800 --> 00:25:59.599
harder about what kind of workloads you're running, how predictable are they?

00:25:59.599 --> 00:26:04.199
And you know, you might be sitting somewhere in between the more simple approaches or the

00:26:04.199 --> 00:26:08.800
more complex approaches, depending on the type of work that your team does.

00:26:09.199 --> 00:26:16.560
Yes, you can go to the next slide, Lou.

00:26:16.560 --> 00:26:21.880
So there are a number of different solutions that you can implement in the cloud to implement

00:26:21.880 --> 00:26:26.560
your architecture from the very simple to the more complex.

00:26:26.560 --> 00:26:31.319
As Lou alluded to, there is something like a quick start image for most cloud providers

00:26:32.319 --> 00:26:40.319
in AWS, and I provided some AWS analogous examples throughout this presentation.

00:26:40.319 --> 00:26:44.839
In AWS, we have something called an Amazon machine image, and this is just a pre-configured

00:26:44.839 --> 00:26:49.160
image where you can quickly spin up the machine and test it out.

00:26:49.160 --> 00:26:54.199
So this is better for maybe short term projects or where we typically recommend this be used

00:26:54.199 --> 00:26:57.800
is in cases where people really just want to kind of play around with RStudio and see

00:26:57.800 --> 00:27:01.239
is it worth investing their time into.

00:27:01.239 --> 00:27:04.719
So they can quickly launch it and test it out and get it up and running without too

00:27:04.719 --> 00:27:06.319
much work.

00:27:06.319 --> 00:27:09.839
And so this is a good for a prototyping phase or just kind of seeing what RStudio is all

00:27:09.839 --> 00:27:10.839
about.

00:27:10.839 --> 00:27:14.040
If you're maybe new to that or you're maybe new to cloud and seeing does it work well

00:27:14.040 --> 00:27:17.560
with your different systems, but it comes at a bit of a premium.

00:27:17.560 --> 00:27:20.400
And so, as Lou was saying, you probably want to make sure you don't leave it on all the

00:27:20.400 --> 00:27:21.400
time.

00:27:21.400 --> 00:27:24.640
You're going to get charged by the hour for your machine and the license fees.

00:27:24.640 --> 00:27:30.040
And really, if you're going to go ahead and deploy RStudio in a truly productionized manner

00:27:30.040 --> 00:27:34.199
and a serious enterprise situation, you're going to want to consider one of the other

00:27:34.199 --> 00:27:36.359
options.

00:27:36.359 --> 00:27:41.880
And so the simplest approach you can take is a virtual machine.

00:27:41.880 --> 00:27:47.239
Deployed on a VPC in AWS, they have something called the Elastic Complete Cloud, and that's

00:27:47.239 --> 00:27:49.839
their virtual machine deployment.

00:27:49.839 --> 00:27:55.520
And so EC2 instances, as recalled, you can go ahead and pick all the RAM and CPU requirements

00:27:55.520 --> 00:27:56.520
that you need.

00:27:56.520 --> 00:27:57.520
Pick the right OS.

00:27:57.520 --> 00:28:00.280
That can be a very important consideration for some teams.

00:28:00.280 --> 00:28:05.560
If you need a Red Hat Linux environment or do you need to or are you OK with an open

00:28:05.560 --> 00:28:08.680
source environment like Ubuntu?

00:28:08.680 --> 00:28:11.719
You want to consider then you want to be highly available or not.

00:28:11.719 --> 00:28:15.560
And if you need double redundancy, this is this is something we often recommend that

00:28:15.560 --> 00:28:20.800
people are working in the cloud is RStudio has a built in load balancer that will distribute

00:28:20.800 --> 00:28:22.920
traffic evenly across the different machines.

00:28:22.920 --> 00:28:27.439
If you've got multiple machines running, but you can implement some double redundancy,

00:28:27.439 --> 00:28:32.079
which is super important for a lot of teams to make sure that if the master goes down,

00:28:32.079 --> 00:28:34.719
you don't lose access to your environment.

00:28:34.719 --> 00:28:38.800
And so we use load balancers in the cloud and every every major cloud provider has some

00:28:38.800 --> 00:28:41.199
version of this.

00:28:41.199 --> 00:28:47.479
And this ultimately allows for us to scale our resources vertically so we can or, you

00:28:47.479 --> 00:28:49.959
know, you can actually scale it out horizontally as well.

00:28:50.959 --> 00:28:56.119
Typically, if you're doing that, we recommend the next approach, which is Kubernetes.

00:28:56.119 --> 00:29:00.439
So just for those who may be uninitiated, you know, scaling vertically will be just

00:29:00.439 --> 00:29:06.359
increasing the amount of RAM or CPU that your machine has versus scaling horizontally is

00:29:06.359 --> 00:29:09.560
simply adding more of the same machine.

00:29:09.560 --> 00:29:12.520
But if you're going to go with that approach, we recommend going with a cluster approach.

00:29:12.520 --> 00:29:16.400
So if you've got a larger team and you've got variable workloads, you might want to

00:29:16.400 --> 00:29:18.319
consider using something like Kubernetes.

00:29:18.400 --> 00:29:21.959
And so, again, every cloud provider has their own version of this.

00:29:21.959 --> 00:29:27.819
On Amazon, they've got a managed service called Amazon EKS or Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service.

00:29:27.819 --> 00:29:30.920
And this is really great for enterprises that have variable workloads.

00:29:30.920 --> 00:29:36.880
And also, if you want to version control your environment, you can use Docker to containerize

00:29:36.880 --> 00:29:41.199
your solutions, your environment and scale this infinitely to your team's needs.

00:29:41.199 --> 00:29:48.119
So if your team grows, you just configure your cluster to grow with your team.

00:29:48.119 --> 00:29:52.439
And again, utilize those load balancers.

00:29:52.439 --> 00:29:55.839
The final one here that I want to point out, and that's an inbuilt feature that's come

00:29:55.839 --> 00:30:00.199
out in our studio in the last couple of years that some people may be aware of, and that's

00:30:00.199 --> 00:30:01.959
a server pro launcher.

00:30:01.959 --> 00:30:03.959
And this integrates well with Kubernetes.

00:30:03.959 --> 00:30:07.479
So what this allows you to do is within your regular environment.

00:30:07.479 --> 00:30:13.439
So maybe you've got pretty low compute needs on an everyday basis within your team.

00:30:13.439 --> 00:30:15.880
So maybe you don't need an EKS environment.

00:30:15.880 --> 00:30:17.520
Maybe you're OK with an EC2 instance.

00:30:17.920 --> 00:30:22.599
But every once in a while, you want the ability to scale up your jobs to a much larger scale.

00:30:22.599 --> 00:30:27.000
And so that's where Job Launcher can be really effective at allowing power users to run those

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:32.319
heavy workloads without bringing to a halt the base instances.

00:30:32.319 --> 00:30:36.319
So if you've got a team of 10 data scientists, they're all working and they're using their

00:30:36.319 --> 00:30:42.439
EC2 instance and somebody wants to run a really heavy model training or simulation, they can

00:30:42.439 --> 00:30:47.520
utilize this Job Launcher and not take down or tank the entire EC2 instance for everybody

00:30:47.520 --> 00:30:48.520
else.

00:30:48.520 --> 00:30:53.319
And so it isolates that workload from everybody else in the team.

00:30:53.319 --> 00:30:57.719
You can go to the next slide.

00:30:57.719 --> 00:31:01.359
So pay as you go, only pay for what you use.

00:31:01.359 --> 00:31:08.160
This is one of the great benefits of cloud, but only if you do it right.

00:31:08.160 --> 00:31:12.800
You can definitely get this wrong and end up with a big, unexpected bill.

00:31:12.800 --> 00:31:18.160
So some of the common mistakes that people see is you over provision your resource, and

00:31:18.160 --> 00:31:19.660
this comes down to poor planning.

00:31:19.660 --> 00:31:27.920
So you over overestimate your needs and you essentially just by some percentage amount

00:31:27.920 --> 00:31:33.640
overspend or have machines set up, an architecture set up that is maybe just a little bit too

00:31:33.640 --> 00:31:36.040
much for what you actually needed.

00:31:36.040 --> 00:31:39.880
And you can scale that down and if you're monitoring that well.

00:31:39.880 --> 00:31:41.160
Another one is poor limit planning.

00:31:41.160 --> 00:31:46.959
So most providers will allow you to set limits on your spend or limits on how big you want

00:31:46.959 --> 00:31:51.479
your clusters to get or limits on what machines are different people are allowed to use and

00:31:51.479 --> 00:31:52.479
stuff like that.

00:31:52.479 --> 00:31:57.479
And so if you're not planning that out or if you're not utilizing it at all, like you

00:31:57.479 --> 00:32:01.280
say, with clusters, the cluster will grow to as big of a need as the team use.

00:32:01.280 --> 00:32:05.000
So if you've got a team of data scientists and you don't have any limits set and they

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:08.839
get carried away with themselves, you could end up with a very large bill at the end of

00:32:08.839 --> 00:32:09.839
the month.

00:32:09.839 --> 00:32:16.280
And the last one, as you alluded to, is shutting down those unused resources.

00:32:16.280 --> 00:32:23.920
So what we see in a lot of teams is they use, you know, elastic MapReduce or they use clusters

00:32:23.920 --> 00:32:27.800
and the analysts will turn on their clusters and do their analysis, but they'll forget

00:32:27.800 --> 00:32:28.800
to shut it off.

00:32:28.800 --> 00:32:35.839
So if they're not using scalable infrastructure and they're setting up a lot of a lot of expensive

00:32:35.839 --> 00:32:39.439
machines and they leave it running overnight, you know, that can be a pretty hefty bill

00:32:39.439 --> 00:32:42.239
in the morning for somebody if they forgot to turn things off.

00:32:42.239 --> 00:32:45.839
So you can you can definitely mitigate against these problems.

00:32:45.839 --> 00:32:50.599
So you can be very thoughtful and plan about planning your architecture.

00:32:50.599 --> 00:32:54.079
And this is something where we really work a lot with our clients on and making sure

00:32:54.079 --> 00:32:58.380
that we spend a lot of time in the planning phase when we're not rushing into implementing

00:32:58.959 --> 00:32:59.959
the solutions.

00:32:59.959 --> 00:33:03.180
We really want to make sure that the solution that we're architecting for them is right

00:33:03.180 --> 00:33:05.859
for them now and right for them six months from now.

00:33:05.859 --> 00:33:10.500
So it's the right mix of balancing for what they need today, but also taking into consideration

00:33:10.500 --> 00:33:13.040
what are they going to need in the future.

00:33:13.040 --> 00:33:16.459
Make sure you're utilizing those budgets and monitoring and alerts.

00:33:16.459 --> 00:33:20.339
Be very clever about that and utilize that to the max because that's going to help prevent

00:33:20.339 --> 00:33:24.540
any unexpected bills or any surprises.

00:33:24.540 --> 00:33:25.540
Categorize your spends.

00:33:25.540 --> 00:33:29.619
Make sure that, you know, if you are overspending, you're able to easily pinpoint where in your

00:33:29.619 --> 00:33:37.300
system you're you're overspending so you can, you know, isolate that offending instance

00:33:37.300 --> 00:33:41.380
or cluster and make mitigating actions to that.

00:33:41.380 --> 00:33:45.780
And of course, you need to regularly reassess so, you know, you can plan as much as you

00:33:45.780 --> 00:33:48.459
want, but your team's needs are going to change over time.

00:33:48.459 --> 00:33:52.099
Maybe your team grows or maybe your team is downsizing a little bit and you can you know,

00:33:52.099 --> 00:33:57.819
you can go with a smaller size, but you need to regularly come back to that.

00:33:57.819 --> 00:34:01.859
You can go to the next slide.

00:34:01.859 --> 00:34:04.979
The next key question is how secure is the cloud?

00:34:04.979 --> 00:34:08.739
And like I said earlier, it can really be as secure as you want it to be.

00:34:08.739 --> 00:34:13.060
So a lot of people think, oh, well, if I have my physical infrastructure in-house on the

00:34:13.060 --> 00:34:15.979
premise, that's the most secure I can be.

00:34:15.979 --> 00:34:20.379
But I mean, that's not always the case because you've got to pay for the security within

00:34:20.379 --> 00:34:21.379
your own premise.

00:34:21.659 --> 00:34:22.659
You've got to pay for security guards.

00:34:22.659 --> 00:34:27.659
If you're really concerned about people coming in and doing harm to your infrastructure,

00:34:27.659 --> 00:34:32.379
you've got to maintain that infrastructure and you're going to maintain all the firewalls

00:34:32.379 --> 00:34:34.540
and security around that.

00:34:34.540 --> 00:34:40.500
If you work with the cloud, Amazon and their shared responsibility model or different providers,

00:34:40.500 --> 00:34:47.340
they will maintain the security and integrity of those physical machines and they provide

00:34:47.340 --> 00:34:52.379
all of the software that you need, that you could possibly need to configure the security.

00:34:52.379 --> 00:34:55.340
So really, it can be as secure as you want it to be.

00:34:55.340 --> 00:35:00.780
And that is a real caveat because you need to make sure that you're configuring your

00:35:00.780 --> 00:35:04.459
solutions to be as secure as your requirements might be.

00:35:04.459 --> 00:35:09.739
So if you have a very high security need, you need to scale up your investment in your

00:35:09.739 --> 00:35:13.580
architecture appropriately.

00:35:13.899 --> 00:35:18.139
In different cloud providers, and I'm going to use AWS again as an example, you've got

00:35:18.139 --> 00:35:19.139
different resources.

00:35:19.139 --> 00:35:24.139
So you can have a VPC that's completely private with subnets are completely private or or

00:35:24.139 --> 00:35:26.860
maybe completely public or maybe a mix of the two.

00:35:26.860 --> 00:35:31.100
And you can have different instances in each environment that can speak to each other across

00:35:31.100 --> 00:35:34.580
using what are known as an Amazon, an Amazon resource name.

00:35:34.580 --> 00:35:38.620
But again, in every cloud provider, you've got this ability to allow services to talk

00:35:38.620 --> 00:35:41.659
to each other without having humans have access to those services.

00:35:41.820 --> 00:35:45.739
So this is really powerful if you want to utilize serverless technology, maybe have

00:35:45.739 --> 00:35:47.580
an entry point that a human can interact with.

00:35:47.580 --> 00:35:51.979
But the underlying hardware or data or infrastructure, they can't access.

00:35:51.979 --> 00:35:56.219
It's only the actual services on AWS that they do have access that can do that.

00:35:57.020 --> 00:35:59.260
So if you go to the next slide, we can see an example of that.

00:35:59.899 --> 00:36:04.139
And this is just an example where we've got two VPCs, their private subnets inside of

00:36:04.139 --> 00:36:04.620
them.

00:36:04.620 --> 00:36:08.139
Ordinarily, these two instances shouldn't be able to interact with each other.

00:36:08.860 --> 00:36:11.179
But again, Amazon provide the software.

00:36:11.179 --> 00:36:14.780
You can use this VPC peering connection and make sure that these instances are now able

00:36:14.780 --> 00:36:16.300
to communicate with each other.

00:36:16.300 --> 00:36:20.860
So a malicious actor cannot communicate with these private subnets or the private instances.

00:36:21.580 --> 00:36:24.540
But you can actually configure these services to be able to talk to each other.

00:36:24.540 --> 00:36:29.179
And that can be really powerful and important for a lot of use cases and making sure that

00:36:29.179 --> 00:36:32.939
your different systems across your organization are able to talk to each other without

00:36:32.939 --> 00:36:33.979
compromising security.

00:36:34.860 --> 00:36:36.699
You can go to the next slide.

00:36:39.020 --> 00:36:44.060
Again, just to point out, this is an example here of the AWS shared responsibility model.

00:36:44.060 --> 00:36:49.739
And just really to point out that it's up to your organization to configure a secure

00:36:49.739 --> 00:36:50.219
environment.

00:36:50.219 --> 00:36:53.260
So that's your portion of the shared responsibility model.

00:36:53.260 --> 00:37:00.300
AWS will provide and maintain the software and hardware needed to to do all that.

00:37:00.300 --> 00:37:06.780
But you need you need to take responsibility for making sure that your privacy and security

00:37:06.780 --> 00:37:08.699
is meeting your requirements.

00:37:08.699 --> 00:37:12.540
So if you're from a highly regulated industry, you need to consider that.

00:37:12.540 --> 00:37:17.100
There's also some government cloud options that if you're working in a government agency,

00:37:18.060 --> 00:37:21.899
most providers have an option that's exclusive to the government agencies.

00:37:23.340 --> 00:37:24.699
That can be very important as well.

00:37:25.739 --> 00:37:26.860
You can go to the next slide.

00:37:27.260 --> 00:37:35.260
Again, I want to keep on the track of this shared responsibility model, and we're talking

00:37:35.260 --> 00:37:37.260
about the stability of environments.

00:37:37.260 --> 00:37:41.979
So if I don't have access or I don't have I don't control my physical infrastructure,

00:37:41.979 --> 00:37:45.500
how can I ensure that it's going to be safe, that everything's going to be safeguarded?

00:37:45.500 --> 00:37:48.219
And what happens if there is a disaster?

00:37:48.219 --> 00:37:49.739
And I'm not going to lose all my data.

00:37:49.739 --> 00:37:50.939
I'm going to lose all my services.

00:37:50.939 --> 00:37:56.620
And again, you really can take advantage of the scale of the cloud in this in this sense.

00:37:56.620 --> 00:38:01.739
So, yes, if you were to architect your solutions poorly, and that's, you know, that's your

00:38:01.739 --> 00:38:07.419
portion of the shared responsibility model, you can expose yourself to instability within

00:38:07.419 --> 00:38:08.939
the cloud infrastructure.

00:38:09.580 --> 00:38:13.340
So you want to make sure when you're architecting your solutions that you're taking advantage

00:38:13.340 --> 00:38:16.379
of some of the features that cloud providers have.

00:38:16.379 --> 00:38:22.860
So in the case of AWS, they've got many regions around the world, dozens of them, and they're

00:38:22.860 --> 00:38:24.379
constantly adding these regions.

00:38:25.020 --> 00:38:29.100
And they also then have within those regions many different availability zones.

00:38:29.100 --> 00:38:33.419
These are geographically distinct areas within those geographically distinct areas.

00:38:33.979 --> 00:38:36.060
And finally, within those, they have data centers.

00:38:36.060 --> 00:38:38.139
And these are where your actual machines live.

00:38:39.340 --> 00:38:45.020
So if you want to make sure that you don't you aren't hit by a disaster and you lose

00:38:45.020 --> 00:38:49.419
all your data or you lose all of your computers or you lose access to your systems, you can

00:38:49.419 --> 00:38:52.219
architect solutions that mitigate for that.

00:38:52.219 --> 00:38:56.860
And in that way, you know, the cloud can be way more scalable and way more secure and

00:38:56.860 --> 00:39:01.580
stable than any on premise solution could ever be if you take advantage of this cloud.

00:39:01.580 --> 00:39:03.739
And that means you just got to architect it carefully.

00:39:03.739 --> 00:39:08.060
And if you go to the next slide, we can have a look here and you can see, yeah, we can

00:39:08.060 --> 00:39:13.020
go and we can make sure if we if we need if we have a global team and we want this highly

00:39:13.020 --> 00:39:18.860
available environment, we want to make sure that we've got our our our systems mirrored

00:39:18.860 --> 00:39:20.780
across many different regions.

00:39:20.780 --> 00:39:26.139
So that means if something happens in the Oregon region and one of the data centers

00:39:27.179 --> 00:39:33.739
experiences a big outage, which can happen, it's OK because we've got a mirrored environment

00:39:33.739 --> 00:39:34.860
inside of North Virginia.

00:39:36.379 --> 00:39:39.260
And so our analysts, our data scientists can continue to do their work.

00:39:40.139 --> 00:39:44.379
You also want to make sure you're setting up disaster recovery effectively so that,

00:39:44.379 --> 00:39:49.100
you know, if you if you do have one region, still make sure you're backing up your data

00:39:49.100 --> 00:39:52.939
in separate areas, especially if you've got mission critical information in your

00:39:52.939 --> 00:39:53.580
infrastructure.

00:39:54.379 --> 00:39:58.379
So just making it, you know, just making that point that, you know, data centers can

00:39:58.379 --> 00:39:59.659
fare, can fail.

00:40:00.939 --> 00:40:02.379
Machines can fail.

00:40:02.379 --> 00:40:03.340
This is the reality.

00:40:03.899 --> 00:40:08.219
Cloud providers take advantage of that scale and the expertise they have in-house to mitigate

00:40:08.219 --> 00:40:10.459
against that and reduce that down as much as they can.

00:40:11.179 --> 00:40:16.860
But it's on you to make sure that you architect solutions that also prevents that as much

00:40:16.860 --> 00:40:17.419
as possible.

00:40:19.739 --> 00:40:21.260
OK, you can go to the next slide, Lou.

00:40:23.659 --> 00:40:28.860
And yeah, there's just closing remarks then on architecting on cloud and the different

00:40:28.860 --> 00:40:35.020
solutions, just tying back to, again, that idea of of scale and you can plan as well

00:40:35.020 --> 00:40:39.179
as you want and you can build your team out or you can plan your architectures as well

00:40:39.179 --> 00:40:42.780
as you want around your current needs and maybe even project your needs a little bit

00:40:42.780 --> 00:40:43.419
into the future.

00:40:43.419 --> 00:40:47.739
But oftentimes what we see is people want to be very conservative.

00:40:47.739 --> 00:40:50.459
They're like, oh, I don't know how this is going to get adopted.

00:40:50.459 --> 00:40:54.620
And then lo and behold, because it's such great software, especially our studio team

00:40:54.620 --> 00:40:58.620
connected is something that sees a great a lot of adoption once it starts getting circulated

00:40:58.620 --> 00:40:59.739
within organizations.

00:41:00.699 --> 00:41:03.340
Suddenly your demand for those services will spike.

00:41:03.979 --> 00:41:06.699
And so you want to be able to respond to that effectively.

00:41:06.699 --> 00:41:10.060
Now, if you're using on premise servers, you're using physical infrastructure in your

00:41:10.060 --> 00:41:10.379
house.

00:41:11.020 --> 00:41:15.659
That means you got to go and you got to call up your your hardware provider and order new

00:41:15.659 --> 00:41:19.659
machines and have them shipped to your site and then have your IT team install them and

00:41:19.659 --> 00:41:21.979
configure them and install the software on them.

00:41:21.979 --> 00:41:23.820
And it's a it's a time lag.

00:41:23.820 --> 00:41:26.780
So you're adding weeks onto your process with cloud.

00:41:26.780 --> 00:41:30.939
If you're clever and you've automated your deployments in an effective way, which you

00:41:30.939 --> 00:41:38.459
can do with stuff like cloud formation, it means that, yeah, I can I can scale up my

00:41:38.459 --> 00:41:42.379
architecture as quickly as I want to get it scaled up and take advantage of that infinite

00:41:42.379 --> 00:41:43.100
scale in the team.

00:41:43.580 --> 00:41:48.459
So if you're planning on a lot of scale, you know, consider that maybe you need to use

00:41:48.459 --> 00:41:53.419
a clustered approach if you if you think your team's really going to grow or just just be

00:41:53.419 --> 00:41:59.580
aware of the different the different growth that your team might experience and take advantage

00:41:59.580 --> 00:42:03.260
of the monitoring that different cloud providers have to monitor that usage.

00:42:03.260 --> 00:42:05.580
You know, in AWS, you have cloud watch.

00:42:05.580 --> 00:42:08.219
You can really monitor that, monitor that.

00:42:08.219 --> 00:42:13.659
And our studio professional has inbuilt monitoring so you can build custom monitoring solutions,

00:42:13.659 --> 00:42:19.260
but keep a close eye on on usage patterns and understand when you need to scale it up.

00:42:19.260 --> 00:42:25.820
And then if you've got a clever architect or cloud cloud engineer, you can easily scale

00:42:25.820 --> 00:42:33.020
up your your solutions with without that time lag of ordering and procuring that physical

00:42:33.020 --> 00:42:33.580
infrastructure.

